  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA4-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaivaṉ ciṟaippuṟattāṉākat tōḻi alar accan tōṉṟac colli varaivu kaṭāyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is [how] the confidante asked for marriage by saying that the fear of gossip has come up.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA4">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            kāṉalañ ciṟukuṭik kaṭaṉmēm paratavar</l>
<l>            nīṉiṟap puṉṉaik koḻuniḻa lacaiit</l>
<l>            taṇperum parappi ṉoṇpata nōkki</l>
<l>            yaṅka ṇarilvalai yuṇakkun tuṟaivaṉō</l>
<l>            ṭalarē yaṉṉai yaṟiyi ṉivaṇuṟai <supplied>vāḻkkai</supplied></l>
<l>            yariya vāku namakkeṉa kūṟiṟ</l>
<l>            koṇṭuñ celvarko ṟōḻi yumaṇar</l>
<l>            veṇka luppiṉ koḷḷai cāṟṟik</l>
<l>            kaṇanirai kiḷarkku neṭuneṟic cakaṭa</l>
<l>            maṇaṉmaṭut turaṟu mōcai kaḻaṉik </l>
<l>            karuṅkāl veṇkuruku verūu</l>
<l>            miruṅkaḻic cērppiṟṟa muṟaivi ṉūrkkē.</l>

        </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
        <l rend="indent">“The gossip about the man from the ghat,</l>
        <l rend="indent">where fishermen, [their] little homes by the seashore grove close to the sea,</l>
        <l rend="indent">stay in the rich shade of the blue-coloured Puṉṉai tree,</l>
        <l rend="indent">look over the bright water<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">patam</term>, "proper consistency", is more likely "look for the proper time", presumably for fishing, but this is difficult to combine with the adjective oṇ, "bright".</note> in a cool, vast expanse,</l>
        <l rend="indent">[and] let [their] interlaced nets with pretty holes dry,</l>
        <l rend="indent4">– if mother gets to know, staying here</l>
        <l>will be difficult<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ariya</term>: how to account for the n.pl. here? T.V.G., following the printed text and reading <term xml:lang="ta">vāḻkkai</term>, explains HER "livelihood" as consisting of two tasks (apart from meeting HIM), namely drying the fish and chasing the birds away from it. Another possibility is the inclusion of the confidante: the lives of both of them will be difficult. A third possibility is to see the "modern" form of the adjective, for which there are a few possible parallels (none of them unequivocal, but understood in that way by T.V.G.): cf. KT 9.2 <term xml:lang="ta">tamiya</term>, KT 62.4 <term xml:lang="ta">naṟiya</term>, KT 77.5 <term xml:lang="ta">aṟiya</term>.</note> for us” – if we tell [him] so,</l>
        <l>will he take [us] along<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">koṇṭum celvar</term>: here one is reminded of the modern <term xml:lang="ta">idiom koṇṭu pō</term>, "to take". The point is clearly HIS returning to his village with HER, and perhaps the -um expresses coincidence, i.e. literally: "will he go having taken [us with him] too".</note>, friend, to the village</l>
        <l rend="indent">where his [people] stay<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">am uṟaiviṉ</term>: here the oblique form <term xml:lang="ta">tam</term> might refer not the village where HE stays (for which we would expect <term xml:lang="ta">tām uṟaiviṉ</term>), but the place where his family lives. Slightly strange remains in any case the use of the plural form here, since in line 4 HE is referred to as <term xml:lang="ta">tuṟaivaṉ</term>, singular.</note>, on the coast with dark backwaters,</l>
        <l rend="indent2">where the black-legged white egret is frightened in the fields</l>
        <l rend="indent2">by the sound, which rumbles when the cart [wheel] gets stuck in</l>
	    <l rend="indent3">the sands, on the long way, where cattle in groups are roused,</l>
	    <l rend="indent3">when salt-merchants proclaim the price of white salt stones.</l>

        

         
        </lg>
        
      </div>
